The corn heads range from the C6R six row 30in head all the way up to the C18F 20in folding corn head. Paired with an X9100, this header allows the large combine to harvest 7,200 bushels of corn per hour. The farm featured in this video is harvesting their crop with two John Deere X9100 combines equipped with the C16F corn head. The C16F, in addition to picking corn in a hurry, also helps to size and reduce the amount of residue out in the field. It's equipped with Romax chopping stock rolls, which help chop up the stocks into pieces that are 6 in or less, which help speed up the breakdown and burial of the residue left out in the field without it washing or blowing away. The headers are also equipped with John Deere stock deflectors which are used to push down the stubble and fracture it which again helps in the breakdown of the residue and it also reduces the chance of damage to the tires and tracks on the combines. These deflectors are placed behind each row unit across the header. You can see from the aerial views of the video how the Romax units and stock stompers leave the residue in the field as flat as a pancake.
